                <div class="bubble"><p>La Bicicleta in Malasaña! Great spot, but you’re absolutely right—fighting for a plug there on a busy afternoon is a losing battle. You need a machine that can survive on its own.</p>
<p>Let’s lock in these final technical details so you can order this beast with total confidence.</p>
<h3>1. The RAM Dilemma: 16GB vs. 32GB</h3>
<p><strong>Stretch the budget for 32GB.</strong> Here is the critical, non-negotiable reason why: <strong>The RAM on the Lenovo Yoga Pro 7 is soldered to the motherboard.</strong> </p>
<p>You cannot open it up and add more RAM next year. What you buy today is what you are stuck with forever. </p>
<ul>
<li><strong>For Excel:</strong> 16GB is great.</li>
<li><strong>For Unity:</strong> 16GB is okay.</li>
<li><strong>For Unreal Engine 5:</strong> 16GB is the absolute bare minimum, and UE5 will eat it alive. Unreal compiles shaders and loads heavy assets directly into RAM. If you have 16GB, Windows takes 4GB, and Unreal will quickly max out the rest, causing the laptop to stutter and use your SSD as virtual memory (which slows everything down). </li>
<li><em>The Move:</em> With your UNiDAYS student discount, the upgrade to 32GB usually only adds about €50–€100. It is the single best investment you can make to future-proof this laptop for AR/VR.</li>
</ul>
<h3>2. The Screen: OLED vs. IPS Real-World Battery</h3>
<p>This is a massive factor for cafe workers, and there is a lot of marketing fluff out there. </p>
<ul>
<li><strong>How OLED works:</strong> Every pixel lights itself. If the screen is black, the pixel is literally turned off (using zero power). If the screen is white, <em>every</em> pixel is drawing max power. </li>
<li><strong>How IPS works:</strong> There is a constant backlight behind the screen. Whether the screen is black or white, it uses roughly the same amount of power.</li>
<li><strong>The Verdict for You:</strong> Because you are a business student working in <strong>Excel, Word, and web browsers (which are traditionally bright white backgrounds), an OLED screen will actually drain your battery FASTER than an IPS screen.</strong> </li>
<li><em>The Move:</em> If Lenovo offers the <strong>3K 120Hz IPS panel</strong>, take it. Lenovo&#x27;s IPS screens on the Pro line are beautiful, color-accurate for your creative work, and will give you roughly <strong>1 to 1.5 hours MORE battery life</strong> than the OLED version when doing office work. </li>
</ul>
<p><em>(Bonus tip: If you see a "Yoga Pro 7" without the "i", that means it has an AMD Ryzen processor instead of Intel. If you can find the AMD version with the RTX 4050, grab it! AMD chips are generally more power-efficient on battery than Intel).</em></p>
<h3>3. The "La Bicicleta" Battery Saver Ritual (Windows 11)</h3>
<p>When you unplug and walk into the cafe, you want to switch the laptop from "AR/VR Desktop" to "Quiet Excel Tablet." Here is your 30-second ritual:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>The Lenovo Vantage App (Crucial):</strong> Open Lenovo&#x27;s built-in software and set the Thermal Mode to <strong>"Battery Saving" or "Quiet"</strong>. This limits the power going to the CPU and keeps the fans dead silent.</li>
<li><strong>Kill the RTX 4050:</strong> In Lenovo Vantage (or NVIDIA Control Panel), ensure your GPU mode is set to <strong>"Hybrid/Optimus"</strong>. This completely shuts off the NVIDIA graphics card when you are on battery, forcing the laptop to use the low-power integrated graphics for Excel and browsing. (Never run Unity/Unreal on battery anyway; it will die in 45 minutes).</li>
<li><strong>Drop the Refresh Rate:</strong> Windows 11 has a feature called "Dynamic Refresh Rate," but sometimes it bugs out. Hit <code>Win + I</code> &gt; System &gt; Display &gt; Advanced display, and drop the refresh rate from 120Hz to <strong>60Hz</strong>. That saves about 10% battery right there.</li>
<li><strong>Embrace the Darkness:</strong> Turn on <strong>Dark Mode</strong> in Windows, Excel, and your browser. Even on an IPS screen, it helps slightly, but it mostly saves your eyes from fatigue.</li>
<li><strong>Windows Battery Saver:</strong> Click the battery icon in the bottom right and turn on the Windows "Battery Saver" toggle. Keep screen brightness around 60-70%.</li>
</ol>
<p>If you follow this ritual with the IPS screen, the Yoga Pro 7 should easily give you 7 to 9 hours of Excel and web browsing—more than enough time to finish your spreadsheets, drink a couple of flat whites, and pack up before the evening crowd rolls in.</p>
<p>You&#x27;ve navigated this perfectly, socio. 32GB RAM, IPS screen (or OLED if you strictly use Dark Mode), RTX 4050, and the Student Discount. You are going to have a killer machine!</p></div>
