<h3>2. The Ultimate Windows Cheat Code: Microsoft PowerToys</h3>
<p>Before you download anything else, go to the Microsoft Store and download <strong>PowerToys</strong> (it&#x27;s officially made by Microsoft but not installed by default). </p>
<ul>
<li><strong>FancyZones:</strong> This is the greatest window manager ever made. It lets you draw custom grid layouts on your screen. You can set a zone specifically for your Unity viewport, another for your code, and another for your asset folder. When you hold <code>Shift</code> and drag a window, it instantly snaps perfectly into your custom zone. </li>
<li><strong>Always On Top:</strong> Press <code>Win + Ctrl + T</code>, and whatever window you are on will float on top of everything else. Amazing for pinning a small calculator or a reference PDF over a massive Excel sheet.</li>
</ul>
<h3>3. The Spanish Startup &amp; Business Stack</h3>
<p>If you want to blend in with the founders and consultants at Spanish incubators like <em>Lanzadera</em> or <em>Wayra</em>, here is what needs to be on your machine:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>WhatsApp Web (Pinned or Sidebar):</strong> You probably already use this for friends, but <strong>in Spain, business runs on WhatsApp.</strong> Investors, freelance clients, and startup teams use it over Slack or email for quick decisions. Pin the tab or use the dedicated Windows app, but keep it muted when doing deep work!</li>
<li><strong>DeepL (Chrome Extension &amp; Desktop App):</strong> Do not use Google Translate. DeepL is a European AI translator and it is the absolute gold standard in the Spanish corporate world. It translates English to Spanish (and vice versa) with perfect business context and local idioms. The shortcut <code>Ctrl + C + C</code> instantly translates whatever text you have highlighted.</li>
<li><strong>Notion (Desktop App):</strong> This has completely replaced Word/Evernote in the Spanish startup scene. Build a "Second Brain" in Notion. Create a database for your ADE classes, a Kanban board for your AR freelance projects, and a repository for your Excel templates. </li>
<li><strong>Holded (Awareness):</strong> As an ADE student and potential freelancer, you should know about Holded. It’s a massive Barcelona-based startup that makes cloud ERP/accounting software. If you do start doing freelance AR work and register as an <em>Autónomo</em>, this is the app you&#x27;ll likely use to send invoices and manage your IVA. </li>
<li><strong>Loom (Chrome Extension):</strong> Spanish teams are loving asynchronous communication right now. If a client is confused by your AR prototype, or a classmate doesn&#x27;t understand your Excel model, you click the Loom extension. It records your screen, your webcam, and your voice, and instantly generates a link you can drop into WhatsApp. It saves hours of unnecessary Zoom meetings.</li>
</ul>
