        </div>
        <div class="turn assistant">
            <div class="turn-label">Assistant</div>
            <div>
                <div class="bubble"><p>I am not "encouraging" you to invest in crypto; I am explaining how many modern investors use it as a <strong>"satellite" holding.</strong></p>
<p>The reason some people suggest a tiny amount (rather than zero) is based on two concepts:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Asymmetric Upside:</strong> Unlike a stock, which might double or triple, certain crypto assets have shown the potential for massive, exponential growth. A very small amount (e.g., 1%) can significantly boost total portfolio returns if it "moons," while a total loss of that 1% won&#x27;t ruin your life.</li>
<li><strong>Diversification (Non-Correlation):</strong> Crypto often moves differently than stocks and bonds. In a portfolio, having an asset that doesn&#x27;t always follow the traditional market can theoretically improve your risk-adjusted returns.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>However, if you have zero interest in it or zero tolerance for its extreme volatility, "None" is a perfectly valid and professional strategy.</strong> </p>
<p>The most important rule is: <strong>Never let speculation (crypto) replace your foundation (stocks and bonds).</strong></p></div>
                <div class="thought reaction">
