                <div class="bubble"><p>Here are four more advanced science project ideas tailored for a high school senior (17yo). These emphasize scientific method—hypothesis, variables, data collection, analysis (e.g., graphs/tables)—and real-world applications. All under $27 total (using dollar store/Walmart basics or household items), buildable/testable in 1-2 days. I&#x27;ve added a concise scientific explanation for each.</p>
<h3>1. <strong>Pendulum Period Investigation</strong> (Physics: Simple Harmonic Motion)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Materials</strong>: String ($1), assorted weights (nuts/bolts from hardware ~$3), protractor/phone timer app, meter stick ($2).</li>
<li><strong>How</strong>: Build pendulums of varying lengths/masses/angles. Measure 10 swings, calculate period (T=2π√(L/g)). Graph period vs. length/mass. Hypothesis: Period independent of mass.</li>
<li><strong>Explanation</strong>: Demonstrates the math of oscillatory motion (T ∝ √length). Relevant to clocks, earthquakes, engineering (bridges). Analyze data for real-world precision.</li>
<li><strong>Time/Cost</strong>: 2 hrs setup + testing. ~$6.</li>
</ul>
<h3>2. <strong>Electrolytic Rust Removal</strong> (Electrochemistry)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Materials</strong>: 9V battery ($2), wires/alligator clips ($3), table salt ($1), plastic container, rusty nails/steel wool (scavenge or $2).</li>
<li><strong>How</strong>: Submerge rusty object as anode in salt water, connect battery. Time rust removal at different voltages/concentrations. Measure mass loss, photo before/after.</li>
<li><strong>Explanation</strong>: Electrolysis drives oxidation-reduction (Fe → Fe²⁺ + 2e⁻). Sacrificial anode protects cathode. Industrial apps: ship hulls, artifacts restoration. Test Faraday&#x27;s laws quantitatively.</li>
<li><strong>Time/Cost</strong>: 1 hr setup + overnight run. ~$8.</li>
</ul>
<h3>3. <strong>Coffee Filter Chromatography</strong> (Chemistry: Separation Science)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Materials</strong>: Coffee filters ($2), black markers/pens (household), rubbing alcohol ($2), beakers/jars ($3), food dyes ($1).</li>
<li><strong>How</strong>: Dot inks on filter strips, suspend in solvents (water/alcohol). Measure pigment Rf values (distance traveled). Test variables: solvent type, pH.</li>
<li><strong>Explanation</strong>: Partitioning based on polarity (like dissolves like). Used in forensics/pharma for compound ID. Calculate Rf = (spot distance)/(solvent front), graph for analysis.</li>
<li><strong>Time/Cost</strong>: 1 hr. ~$8.</li>
</ul>
<h3>4. <strong>Syringe Boyle&#x27;s Law Demo</strong> (Physics/Chemistry: Gas Laws)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Materials</strong>: 2 large syringes ($4 pack), tubing/clamps ($3), pressure gauge app or manometer (DIY with tube/water ~$2), thermometer.</li>
<li><strong>How</strong>: Seal one syringe, compress air while measuring volume/pressure (phone app). Plot PV=constant graph. Vary temperature.</li>
<li><strong>Explanation</strong>: Boyle&#x27;s Law (P₁V₁=P₂V₂) for ideal gases at constant T. Key to scuba diving, hydraulics, weather balloons. Quantify deviations from ideal gas behavior.</li>
<li><strong>Time/Cost</strong>: 45 min. ~$9.</li>
</ul>
<p>Document with photos, hypothesis/results/discussion (e.g., error analysis). These look impressive for high school—focus on data/math in your presentation. Which one interests you? Good luck!</p></div>
