                <div class="bubble"><p>Great choice! The <strong>Electrolytic Rust Removal</strong> project is perfect for a high school senior—it&#x27;s hands-on electrochemistry with real quantifiable data, math (Faraday&#x27;s laws), and industrial relevance. It&#x27;s safe, cheap (~$8 total), and results are dramatic (visible in hours/overnight). You can run multiple trials in 1-2 days.</p>
<h3><strong>Scientific Background</strong> (for your report/presentation)</h3>
<p>Rust is iron oxide (Fe₂O₃) from oxidation: 4Fe + 3O₂ + 2H₂O → 2Fe₂O₃·H₂O. Electrolysis reverses this:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Anode</strong> (rusty object, +): Rust dissolves (Fe → Fe²⁺ + 2e⁻).</li>
<li><strong>Cathode</strong> (- , e.g., steel wool): Hydrogen gas bubbles (2H₂O + 2e⁻ → H₂ + 2OH⁻), alkaline environment cleans metal.</li>
<li>Salt (NaCl) provides ions for conductivity. Follows Faraday&#x27;s 1st Law: mass ∝ charge passed (Q = I × t).</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Hypothesis</strong>: Higher voltage/salt concentration speeds rust removal (measure mass loss/time).</p>
<h3><strong>Materials</strong> (Dollar store/Walmart/hardware/home: &lt;$10 total)</h3>
<ul>
<li>9V battery or 6V lantern battery ($2).</li>
<li>Alligator clip wires (2-3 pairs, $3).</li>
<li>Table salt (~$1).</li>
<li>Plastic container (e.g., Tupperware, free).</li>
<li>Rusty iron object (nails/tools, scavenge or $2 steel wool/screws).</li>
<li>Digital scale (kitchen/phone app, free) or ruler for volume.</li>
<li>Timer/phone, gloves, towel.</li>
<li>Optional: Multimeter ($5) for current measurement.</li>
</ul>
<h3><strong>Safety First</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>Work in ventilated area (H₂ gas is flammable— no sparks/open flame).</li>
<li>Don&#x27;t touch water during run (low voltage, but unplug first).</li>
<li>Adult supervision if under 18.</li>
<li>Wash hands; don&#x27;t drink electrolyte.</li>
</ul>
<h3><strong>Step-by-Step Build &amp; Experiment</strong> (30 min setup + 4-24 hr run)</h3>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>Prep Rusty Object</strong>:
   - Weigh rusty item (e.g., nail) precisely (e.g., 10.5g). Photo "before."</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Setup Electrolyte</strong>:
   - Fill container 1/2 with warm water + 1-2 tbsp salt (makes ~0.5-1M NaCl solution). Stir.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Assemble Cell</strong>:
   - Cathode: Coil clean steel wool/scrap iron, clip to battery <strong>negative (-)</strong> terminal. Submerge (don&#x27;t touch anode).
   - Anode: Clip rusty object to battery <strong>positive (+)</strong>. Suspend/submerge (wire holds it up, not touching cathode).
   - Connect battery. Bubbles? Good! (H₂ at cathode.)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Run Trials</strong> (Test variables for data):</p>
</li>
</ol>
