<ul>
<li><strong>Better balance</strong>: each part is now clearly ≈ 1/3.  </li>
<li><strong>Tighter thread</strong>: the guiding concept is “from substance to place to anthropological structure.”  </li>
<li><strong>Deeper connection</strong>: Durand is no longer just “credited”; we use his actual technical vocabulary (schèmes ascendants/descendants, contenant/contenu, mythe du centre) which shows real mastery.  </li>
<li><strong>Reduced repetition</strong>: the four-elements-in-the-house motif appears only once, in Part III, as the synthesis.  </li>
<li><strong>Higher conceptual density</strong> while remaining readable in 4 hours.  </li>
<li><strong>Still faithful</strong> to the original question: the main subject remains Bachelard’s poetics of space and the elements; Durand is the <em>horizon</em>, not the center.</li>
</ul>
