        <div class="turn assistant">
            <div class="turn-label">Assistant</div>
            <div>
                <div class="bubble"><p>That €13-€14 price point is the absolute sweet spot in Madrid right now. Inflation has pushed a lot of central <em>menús</em> up to €15+, but if you know where to look, you can still find fantastic value without resorting to heavy, greasy fast food that will make you fall asleep in your afternoon study session.</p>
<p>Since you want to minimize transit time between Malasaña and Chamberí, these three spots are geographically perfect for your route, highly efficient, and will give you great, healthy food for your budget:</p>
<h3>1. Vega Álamo (Conde Duque / Malasaña Border)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Location:</strong> Calle del Álamo, 3 (Just a 5-minute walk from Urbano Café)</li>
<li><strong>The Price:</strong> Usually around €13.50</li>
<li><strong>Why it’s great:</strong> Vega is a fully plant-based restaurant, but you don&#x27;t need to be vegan to appreciate it—the food is genuinely incredible. Their <em>menú del día</em> is famous in the neighborhood for being creative, incredibly healthy, and beautifully plated. You’ll get a starter, main, dessert/coffee, homemade sourdough bread, and a drink. It leaves you feeling energized rather than sluggish, which is exactly what you need before heading back to your laptop. </li>
<li><strong>The Vibe:</strong> Modern, cozy, and very quick service if you let them know you&#x27;re on a lunch break.</li>
</ul>
<h3>2. Honest Greens (Glorieta de Bilbao)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Location:</strong> Calle de Sagasta, 29 (Right on the roundabout separating Malasaña and Chamberí)</li>
<li><strong>The Price:</strong> €10 - €14 (Depends on how you build your plate)</li>
<li><strong>Why it’s great:</strong> <em>Disclaimer: This isn&#x27;t a traditional Spanish "primer y segundo plato" set menu.</em> However, for a business student wanting healthy food, big portions, and zero wasted time, it is unbeatable. You choose a base (like a massive salad or roasted vegetables) and add a high-quality protein (herb chicken, falafel, tataki, etc.). The ingredients are locally sourced, organic, and very fresh. </li>
<li><strong>Pro-tip:</strong> They have a water station with naturally infused fruit waters (mint/lemon, watermelon/basil) that is free with your meal, saving you the €2.50 you&#x27;d normally spend on a drink elsewhere. </li>
</ul>
<h3>3. Casa Macareno (Heart of Malasaña)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Location:</strong> Calle de San Vicente Ferrer, 44 (Perfectly located between La Bicicleta and Chamberí)</li>
<li><strong>The Price:</strong> Around €13.50 - €14.00</li>
<li><strong>Why it’s great:</strong> If you want a traditional Spanish <em>menú del día</em> but want to avoid the heavy, oil-drenched dishes you sometimes find at older taverns, this is the spot. It looks like a classic, old-school Madrid tavern (beautiful tiles and vintage decor), but the kitchen is very modern. They always have healthy options on the daily menu, like a fresh <em>salmorejo</em> (cold tomato puree), grilled fish, or roasted chicken with vegetables. The portions are very generous, and the quality-to-price ratio is outstanding. </li>
</ul>
<p><strong>A quick time-saving tip for a student:</strong> 
The traditional Madrid office lunch rush hits hard at exactly <strong>2:30 PM</strong>. If you want to get in, eat well, and get back to your cafés without waiting in line for a table, try to arrive at these restaurants right when they open for lunch (usually between <strong>1:30 PM and 1:45 PM</strong>). You&#x27;ll get VIP treatment and be back to studying by the time everyone else is just sitting down!</p></div>
                <div class="thought reaction">
                    <span class="thought-label">Reaction</span>
                    <span class="category-tag">Explicit Affirmation</span>
                    I&#x27;m actually so impressed by the &#x27;Honest Greens&#x27; suggestion because the free water tip is exactly the kind of detail a budget-conscious student needs. The AI also understood the geographical &#x27;bridge&#x27; between the two neighborhoods perfectly. I also like the strategic advice about arriving at 1:30 PM to avoid the office rush—it shows the AI does understand the local culture and my need for time efficiency.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="turn user">
            <div class="turn-label">User</div>
            <div>
                <div class="bubble">Actually, for Thursday, I&#x27;m meeting up with two other classmates from my degree to work on a group project. We&#x27;ll need a bit more space than a single person, and since we&#x27;ll be discussing things, we need a spot where talking won&#x27;t be seen as a nuisance, but that still has that &#x27;study atmosphere&#x27; so we don&#x27;t get distracted. Out of the cafes you did mention here—or maybe a new one—which would be best for a group of three to collaborate for a couple of hours?</div>
                <div class="thought reason">
                    <span class="thought-label">Reason</span>
                    <span class="category-tag">Task Continuation</span>
                    I&#x27;m introducing kind of a new variable here: a group of people instead of a solo study session. I want to see if the AI can differentiate between &#x27;quiet study&#x27; spots and &#x27;collaborative&#x27; spots. Most specialty cafes in Madrid are tiny, so this is a test of its spatial knowledge of these venues. I&#x27;m also checking if it will warn me about potential issues with groups taking up too much space in small shops...
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="turn assistant">
            <div class="turn-label">Assistant</div>
            <div>
                <div class="bubble"><p>For a group project where you need to discuss ideas without feeling like you&#x27;re whispering in a library, the dynamics definitely change! You need a place with a bit of ambient background noise (so your voices blend in) and larger tables so three laptops don&#x27;t feel like a game of Tetris.</p>
<p>Here is how I would break down your options for Thursday, featuring the best choice from the previous list, plus <strong>one brand-new recommendation</strong> that is arguably the best group-work cafe in the area.</p>
<h3>1. The Best New Addition: Federal Café (Conde Duque / Malasaña)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Location:</strong> Plaza de las Comendadoras, 9</li>
<li><strong>Why it’s perfect for a group:</strong> If you ask Madrid locals where to do a group meeting, Federal is usually the first answer. It is incredibly spacious with massive windows and tons of natural light. More importantly, they have <strong>large, wide communal wooden tables</strong> that are practically designed for spreading out multiple laptops and notebooks. </li>
<li><strong>The Vibe:</strong> It’s a hybrid space. You have people having brunch alongside people coding or studying. Because of this mix, there is a steady, energetic hum of conversation. You and your classmates can freely discuss your business project at a normal volume without getting glared at by someone trying to cram for an exam. </li>
<li><strong>The Coffee/Food:</strong> Excellent specialty coffee, great juices, and a fantastic food menu if your meeting runs long and you need to share some snacks. </li>
</ul>
<h3>2. The Best from the Original List: Monkee Koffee (Chamberí)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Location:</strong> Calle de Vallehermoso, 112</li>
<li><strong>Why it’s perfect for a group:</strong> As mentioned before, Monkee Koffee is very spacious with high ceilings. Those high ceilings are key here—they absorb sound well, meaning the cafe rarely feels "hushed." </li>
<li><strong>The Setup:</strong> They have a massive communal table right in the center of the cafe. If you arrive a bit early and secure a corner of that table, you’ll have plenty of room for three people to sit together, plug in, and collaborate. The vibe is very laid-back, and quiet talking is completely acceptable here.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Where <em>Not</em> to Go for This Specific Meeting:</h3>
<p>Just to save you some awkwardness, I would <strong>skip Urbano</strong> and the <strong>basement of La Bicicleta</strong> for this specific Thursday session. </p>
<ul>
<li>Urbano is quite small, and because it’s heavily populated by solo students deep in focus, a group of three talking might feel a bit too loud. </li>
<li>The basement of La Bicicleta is practically a silent zone. (Though the <em>upstairs</em> of La Bicicleta could work if you manage to snag the big table by the window!).</li>
</ul>
<h3>A Quick Pro-Tip for Group Cafe Work in Madrid:</h3>
<p>Finding three seats together near a power outlet is the hardest part of the Madrid cafe hustle. Since you&#x27;re meeting on a Thursday, try to schedule your meet-up for <strong>10:00 AM or 4:00 PM</strong>. If you try to meet up right at 11:30 AM (peak Spanish coffee break time) or 5:30 PM (afternoon <em>merienda</em> time), finding a cluster of three seats at Federal or Monkee will be entirely down to luck!</p></div>
                <div class="thought reaction">
                    <span class="thought-label">Reaction</span>
                    <span class="category-tag">Explicit Affirmation</span>
                    I really like that the AI redirected me, tbh! It would have been easy to just say &#x27;go to the places I already told you about,&#x27; but it recognized that group work has different spatial and acoustic needs. The recommendation for Federal Café is spot on for Madrid. I also find the specific timing advice (10:00 AM or 4:00 PM) to avoid the Spanish &#x27;merienda&#x27; rush very helpful and realistic for someone living here.
                </div>
