        <div class="turn assistant">
            <div class="turn-label">Assistant</div>
            <div>
                <div class="bubble"><p>I am so glad you liked the dot-grid tip! Once you start using one for business frameworks, you&#x27;ll never go back to lined paper.</p>
<p>Now, onto the most important part of the week: Friday night <em>cañas</em>. </p>
<p>Finding an authentic taberna in Malasaña that hasn&#x27;t been overrun by tourists or turned into an overpriced cocktail bar can be tricky. You want spots that are "castizo" (authentically Madrid) but have a lively, young, local energy. </p>
<p>Here are three fantastic spots in the Malasaña/Chamberí area that offer the real Madrid experience, perfect for a Friday post-study wind-down:</p>
<h3>1. Casa Camacho (The Malasaña Rite of Passage)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Location:</strong> Calle de San Andrés, 4 (Heart of Malasaña)</li>
<li><strong>The Vibe:</strong> This is the definition of an old-school Madrid taberna, and it is an absolute institution for Madrid&#x27;s university students. It’s small, loud, has zero aesthetic pretenses, and the floor is usually covered in napkins. It will be crowded, but crowded with <em>locals</em>, not tourists.</li>
<li><strong>What to order:</strong> You have to order their famous <strong>"Yayo"</strong>. It’s a house-mixed drink made of vermouth, gin, and <em>Casera</em> (a lightly sweetened soda water). It’s cheap, incredibly refreshing, and packs a punch. They’ll usually slide you a free little plate of olives or chips with your drinks. </li>
</ul>
<h3>2. Hermanos Vinagre (The "Neo-Taberna" in Chamberí)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Location:</strong> Calle de Galileo, 56 (Chamberí)</li>
<li><strong>The Vibe:</strong> This is a massive hit with Madrid’s 20-something crowd right now. It is a "neo-taberna"—meaning they took the exact concept of a 19th-century Spanish tavern (standing room, tiled walls, traditional snacks) but updated it with a great playlist and a young, energetic atmosphere. </li>
<li><strong>What to order:</strong> They are famous for two things: perfectly poured <em>cañas</em> and high-quality preserves (<em>conservas</em>). Get a round of beers and order some <strong>Gildas</strong> (a classic Basque skewer of olive, anchovy, and pickled pepper) or their pickled mussels. It’s the ultimate authentic Spanish Friday evening snack.</li>
</ul>
<h3>3. El Doble (The Temple of the Madrid Beer)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Location:</strong> Calle de Ponzano, 58 (Chamberí)</li>
<li><strong>The Vibe:</strong> If you want to experience the absolute pinnacle of Madrid beer culture, you go here. It’s a very traditional, brightly lit, standing-room-only bar. While the decor is old-school, on a Friday evening, it is absolutely packed with young locals kicking off their weekend. </li>
<li><strong>What to order:</strong> Just order a round of <strong>"Dobles"</strong> (a larger glass of beer). The waiters here are considered masters at "tirando cañas" (pulling beers)—they pour it with a perfect, thick two-finger head of foam that keeps the beer carbonated. The best part? They are famous for their generous <strong>free tapas</strong>. With every round of drinks you order, they will drop a plate of food in front of you—usually English-style potato chips with mussels, or fresh shrimp. </li>
</ul>
<h3>🍻 A Quick Madrid Friday Night Pro-Tip:</h3>
<p>If you want to do Friday night like a true local, <strong>don&#x27;t sit down, and don&#x27;t stay in one place.</strong> 
The authentic Madrid way to do Friday evening is called <em>"ir de cañas"</em>. You stand at the bar, order one drink and share a small tapa, and as soon as your glass is empty, you pay and walk to the next bar down the street to do it again. </p>
<p>Also, Madrid locals eat dinner very late (around 9:30 PM or 10:00 PM). If you finish studying and hit these bars around <strong>8:00 PM</strong>, you&#x27;ll be right on time for the "aperitivo de la tarde" and you&#x27;ll actually be able to snag a great spot at the bar before the massive 9:30 PM dinner rush begins!</p>
<p>Have an awesome week of studying, good luck with the group project, and enjoy the Friday cañas! Let me know if you ever need more Madrid tips!</p></div>
