                    satisfied
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="turn user">
            <div class="turn-label">User</div>
            <div>
                <div class="bubble">i&#x27;m in love with a girl, but she set boundary for me</div>
                <div class="thought reason">
                    <span class="thought-label">Reason</span>
                    <span class="category-tag">Task Motivation &amp; Goal</span>
                    i had to confess my feelings
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="turn assistant">
            <div class="turn-label">Assistant</div>
            <div>
                <div class="bubble"><p>That is a really tough and painful situation to be in. It is completely normal to feel hurt, confused, or frustrated when you have strong feelings for someone and they put up a wall or a limit. </p>
<p>First, I want to say that the fact she communicated a boundary to you is actually a sign of maturity. It means she wants to keep you in her life in some capacity, but she needs things to be a certain way for her to feel comfortable and safe. </p>
<p>To navigate this without losing her trust—and while protecting your own heart—here are a few things to keep in mind:</p>
<p><strong>1. Respect the boundary completely</strong>
This is the absolute most important step. If you try to push past her boundary, argue with it, or sneak around it, you will break her trust, and it will likely push her away for good. Respecting her boundary is the highest form of showing you truly care about her. </p>
<p><strong>2. Don&#x27;t view the boundary as a punishment</strong>
Boundaries aren&#x27;t usually about punishing the other person; they are about protecting the person setting them. She is simply telling you, "This is the space I need right now." </p>
<p><strong>3. Check in with your own feelings</strong>
While you must respect her boundaries, <strong>you also have to look out for yourself.</strong> Can you realistically handle the boundary she set? For example, if she said "I only want to be friends," can you actually be <em>just</em> her friend right now without it breaking your heart every time you see her? If the answer is no, it is 100% okay for <em>you</em> to set a boundary, too (like taking some time apart so you can move on).</p>
<p>To help you figure out the best next steps, it would help to know a little more context. If you feel comfortable sharing:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>What specific boundary did she set?</strong> (e.g., "Let&#x27;s just be friends," "I need some space right now," "Please don&#x27;t text me so often," etc.)</li>
<li><strong>How did you respond when she told you?</strong></li>
</ul>
<p>I&#x27;m here to listen without judgment. Take your time.</p></div>
                <div class="thought reaction">
                    <span class="thought-label">Reaction</span>
                    <span class="category-tag">Explicit Affirmation</span>
                    good questions to make the picture clearer
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="turn user">
            <div class="turn-label">User</div>
            <div>
                <div class="bubble">not talk to her too much, also don&#x27;t flirt or do some actions like getting gifts for her</div>
                <div class="thought reason">
                    <span class="thought-label">Reason</span>
                    <span class="category-tag">Task Motivation &amp; Goal</span>
                    i need help
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="turn assistant">
            <div class="turn-label">Assistant</div>
            <div>
                <div class="bubble"><p>Thank you for sharing that. I know how much it hurts to hear those words when you are in love with someone. When you care about a girl, your natural instinct is to talk to her, make her smile, and show her you care by getting her things. Being told to stop doing those exact things feels like rejection, and it is completely normal if your heart is aching right now.</p>
<p>Let’s look honestly at what her boundaries mean, and then figure out what you should do next.</p>
<p><strong>What her boundaries mean:</strong>
By asking you not to talk to her too much, not to flirt, and not to buy gifts, she is sending a very clear message: <strong>She knows you have romantic feelings for her, but she does not feel the same way, and your romantic gestures are making her feel pressured or uncomfortable.</strong> </p>
<p>Gifts and flirting carry romantic weight. When a girl doesn&#x27;t return those feelings, receiving gifts or heavy attention makes her feel guilty or overwhelmed. By setting this boundary, she is trying to remove the romantic pressure so you two can just exist as normal friends or acquaintances. </p>
<p><strong>What you need to do right now:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Stop the gestures immediately:</strong> Do exactly as she asked. Stop buying gifts, stop dropping romantic hints, and stop initiating long or deep conversations. Treat her the exact same way you would treat a casual friend.</li>
<li><strong>Match her energy:</strong> A good rule of thumb right now is to let her come to you. If she texts you, reply politely, but don&#x27;t double-text her or try to keep a dying conversation going. Give her the space she asked for. </li>
<li><strong>Do not try to "win her over" secretly:</strong> Sometimes guys think, <em>"If I just act like a really good friend for a while, she will see how great I am and fall for me."</em> Please do not do this. It rarely works, and it usually ends with you feeling used and deeply hurt.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>The most important question for YOU:</strong>
Right now, you are focused on what <em>she</em> wants. But you need to ask yourself what <em>you</em> need. </p>
<p><strong>Can you realistically be just her casual friend?</strong> 
Being around a girl you are in love with, having to swallow your feelings, pretending you don&#x27;t want to hold her hand, and eventually watching her date other guys—that is emotional torture. </p>
<p>If you cannot handle just being her friend without it breaking your heart every day, <strong>it is 100% okay for you to walk away.</strong> You can say to her: <em>"I completely respect your boundaries and I won&#x27;t flirt or buy you gifts. But because I do have feelings for you, I think I need to take a step back and give us some space so I can move on."</em></p>
<p>Be honest with yourself: Do you think you can handle just being a distant friend right now? Or do you think staying around her is just going to keep hurting you?</p></div>
                <div class="thought reaction">
                    <span class="thought-label">Reaction</span>
                    <span class="category-tag">Explicit Affirmation</span>
                    super advices, make sense
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="turn user">
            <div class="turn-label">User</div>
            <div>
                <div class="bubble">i think i could, but i want to be around her</div>
                <div class="thought reason">
                    <span class="thought-label">Reason</span>
                    <span class="category-tag">Task Motivation &amp; Goal</span>
                    i can&#x27;t get over her
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="turn assistant">
            <div class="turn-label">Assistant</div>
            <div>
                <div class="bubble"><p>It is completely understandable that you feel that way. When you are in love with someone, the thought of not being in their life feels unbearable. It is a very natural human instinct to say, <em>"I will accept whatever rules you give me, as long as I still get to see you."</em></p>
<p>But I want to be very honest with you as a friend: <strong>Staying around someone you are in love with, just to stay in their orbit, is one of the hardest and most painful things you can do to yourself.</strong> </p>
<p>Right now, you are entering what people sometimes call the "proximity trap." You are agreeing to be a friend not because you actually want a platonic friendship, but because you want to be near her. </p>
<p>If you are going to try to do this, you need to go into it with your eyes wide open. Here is what you need to prepare yourself for, and how to handle it:</p>
<p><strong>1. The "Reality Check" Test</strong>
To truly be around her as just a friend, you have to mentally prepare for the hardest parts of friendship. </p>
<ul>
<li>How will you feel if she starts talking to you about a guy she has a crush on?</li>
<li>How will you feel if you see her flirting with someone else?
If the thought of those things makes your chest tight or makes you feel sick, staying around her is going to be emotional torture. You have to actively remind yourself: <em>She is just a friend.</em> </li>
</ul>
<p><strong>2. Use the "Would I do this for a guy friend?" Rule</strong>
Since she asked you not to flirt, buy gifts, or talk too much, you need a compass for how to act. Use this rule: <strong>If you wouldn&#x27;t do it for a buddy, don&#x27;t do it for her.</strong> </p>
<ul>
<li>Would you buy your guy friend a random gift on a Tuesday? No. So don&#x27;t do it for her.</li>
<li>Would you double-text your guy friend if he took 4 hours to reply? No. So don&#x27;t do it to her.
This will help keep you from accidentally crossing her boundaries.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>3. Stick to Group Settings</strong>
Hanging out one-on-one is dangerous right now. It feels too much like a date, and it will feed your romantic feelings. If you want to be around her, try to only do it when other friends are around. It takes the pressure off her, and it helps you see her in a normal, casual environment.</p>
<p><strong>4. Do Not Wait for Her to Change Her Mind</strong>
You have to kill the hope that if you are just a "really good friend" for long enough, she will suddenly realize she loves you. That happens in movies, but in real life, it usually just leads to years of wasted time and a broken heart. You have to accept her boundary as permanent.</p>
<p><strong>You are allowed to change your mind.</strong>
You can try this for a week, or a month. But if you find that you are going home feeling sad, anxious, or drained every time you see her, you have to promise to protect yourself. It is okay to step away later if it becomes too heavy to carry.</p>
<p>Do you guys have to see each other every day? Like, do you go to school together, work together, or share the same friend group?</p></div>
                <div class="thought reaction">
                    <span class="thought-label">Reaction</span>
                    <span class="category-tag">Explicit Affirmation</span>
                    good questions
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </article>

