<h4>📈 How to Run It for Maximum Hypertrophy</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Progressive Overload:</strong> Add 2.5–5 lbs to a lift when you hit the top of the rep range with good form. If you can&#x27;t add weight, add 1 rep or improve tempo/control.</li>
<li><strong>RIR (Reps in Reserve):</strong> Stop each set with <strong>1–3 reps left in the tank</strong>. Going to failure every set hinders recovery and volume quality.</li>
<li><strong>Warm-up:</strong> 5 min light cardio + dynamic mobility, then 2–3 ramp-up sets before your first heavy compound.</li>
<li><strong>Tempo:</strong> Control the eccentric (2–3 sec down), explode up, pause lightly at stretch/contraction if applicable.</li>
<li><strong>Volume:</strong> ~10–18 hard sets per muscle group/week, which is the research-backed sweet spot for most trainees.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3>🥩 Daily Protein Intake</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Target:</strong> <code>0.7–1.0g per pound of bodyweight</code> (1.6–2.2g/kg) daily.</li>
<li><strong>Distribution:</strong> Spread across 3–4 meals, each containing ~20–40g of high-quality protein to maximize muscle protein synthesis (MPS).</li>
<li><em>Example:</em> 170 lb male → ~120–170g protein/day.</li>
</ul>
