<h3>🔍 Quick Verdict</h3>
<p>For exactly 4 training days per week, <strong>Upper/Lower is the clear winner</strong> for hypertrophy. PPL is designed for 3 or 6 days; forcing it into 4 creates uneven frequency, awkward scheduling, and suboptimal recovery.</p>
<hr>
<h3>📊 How Each Split Actually Runs on 4 Days</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Aspect</th>
<th>Upper/Lower (4-Day)</th>
<th>PPL (4-Day)</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><strong>Weekly Structure</strong></td>
<td>Upper A / Lower A / Rest / Upper B / Lower B / Rest / Rest</td>
<td>Push / Pull / Legs / Push (Week 1) → Pull / Legs / Push / Pull (Week 2)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Muscle Frequency</strong></td>
<td>Every major muscle group trained <strong>2x/week</strong></td>
<td>Push muscles: ~2x, Pull muscles: ~1–1.5x, Legs: ~1–1.5x (rotates weekly)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Session Length</strong></td>
<td>~60–75 min, balanced fatigue</td>
<td>Push/Pull days: moderate. Leg day: often 80–90+ min, high systemic fatigue</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Scheduling Flexibility</strong></td>
<td>Fixed &amp; predictable (e.g., Mon/Tue/Thu/Fri)</td>
<td>Requires rotating days or accepting uneven weekly stimulus</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Progressive Overload Tracking</strong></td>
<td>Simple: same movements repeat weekly</td>
<td>Messy: exercise order &amp; frequency shift weekly</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<hr>
<h3>🧠 Why Upper/Lower Wins for 4 Days</h3>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>Optimal Frequency for Hypertrophy</strong><br>
   Meta-analyses consistently show that training each muscle <strong>2x/week</strong> outperforms 1x/week for muscle growth, especially beyond the novice stage. Upper/Lower guarantees this. PPL on 4 days averages ~1.3–1.7x/week depending on the rotation.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Balanced Fatigue &amp; Recovery</strong><br>
   Upper/Lower splits systemic stress evenly. PPL crams all lower-body work into one day, which often leaves you too fatigued to maintain intensity on accessories or recover fully before the next session.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Consistent Volume Distribution</strong><br>
   With Upper/Lower, you can easily hit <code>10–16 hard sets/muscle/week</code> split across two sessions (e.g., 5–8 sets/session). PPL on 4 days forces you to either under-train certain muscles one week, over-train others, or constantly shuffle exercise selection.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Better for Progressive Overload</strong><br>
   Hypertrophy thrives on tracking the same lifts week-to-week. Upper/Lower lets you repeat movement patterns (e.g., Bench A/OHP B, Squat A/Deadlift B) with predictable progression. PPL’s rotating schedule breaks that continuity.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h3>⚠️ When PPL <em>Could</em> Work on 4 Days (and Why It&#x27;s Rarely Ideal)</h3>
<p>You <em>can</em> run a modified 4-day PPL like: <code>Push / Pull / Rest / Legs / Push / Pull / Rest</code> (rotating weekly), but it comes with trade-offs:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Inconsistent stimulus</strong>: Chest/shoulders/triceps get hit twice some weeks, back/biceps once, legs once.</li>
<li><strong>Programming complexity</strong>: You must carefully balance weekly volume to avoid over/under-training.</li>
<li><strong>No proven advantage</strong>: Research shows no hypertrophy benefit to PPL over Upper/Lower when frequency and volume are matched. It’s purely a preference/scheduling tool that shines at 6 days.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3>✅ Bottom Line</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Stick with Upper/Lower</strong> for 4 days. It aligns perfectly with hypertrophy science, simplifies tracking, and maximizes recovery.</li>
<li><strong>Save PPL for 3 or 6 days/week</strong> if you ever expand your schedule.</li>
<li>The program I provided already uses an Upper/Lower structure optimized for 4-day hypertrophy. If you want, I can adjust exercise selection, swap movements for joint comfort, or build a progression tracker next.</li>
</ul>
