<hr>
<h3>🎯 The Gold Standard: Double Progression Method</h3>
<p>For muscle growth, <strong>linear weight jumps every week fail quickly</strong>. Instead, use <strong>Double Progression</strong>:</p>
<ol>
<li>Pick a rep range (e.g., <code>8–12</code>)</li>
<li>Start with a weight you can do for the <strong>bottom</strong> of the range with <code>1–2 Reps in Reserve (RIR)</code></li>
<li>Each week, add reps with the <strong>same weight</strong> until you hit the <strong>top</strong> of the range on all sets</li>
<li>Once you hit the top, increase weight slightly (<code>2.5–5 lbs / 1–2.5 kg</code>) and drop back to the bottom of the range</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Example (Incline DB Press, 3 sets):</strong></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Week</th>
<th>Set 1</th>
<th>Set 2</th>
<th>Set 3</th>
<th>Action</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>1</td>
<td>40 lbs × 8</td>
<td>40 × 8</td>
<td>40 × 8</td>
<td>Start</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>2</td>
<td>40 × 9</td>
<td>40 × 9</td>
<td>40 × 8</td>
<td>+1 rep</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>3</td>
<td>40 × 10</td>
<td>40 × 10</td>
<td>40 × 9</td>
<td>+1 rep</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>4</td>
<td>40 × 12</td>
<td>40 × 11</td>
<td>40 × 10</td>
<td>Hit top range</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>5</td>
<td><strong>45 lbs</strong> × 8</td>
<td>45 × 8</td>
<td>45 × 8</td>
<td><strong>Increase weight, reset</strong></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<hr>
<h3>⚖️ How Much Weight to Add &amp; When</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Lift Type</th>
<th>Increment</th>
<th>When to Add</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><strong>Upper body compounds</strong> (Bench, OHP, Row)</td>
<td>+2.5–5 lbs (1–2.5 kg)</td>
<td>Hit top of rep range on ALL sets with good form + 1 RIR</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Lower body compounds</strong> (Squat, Deadlift, Leg Press)</td>
<td>+5–10 lbs (2.5–5 kg)</td>
<td>Same criteria</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Isolation moves</strong> (Curls, Raises, Pushdowns)</td>
<td>+2.5 lbs or microplates</td>
<td>Often progress better with reps/tempo first</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Never add weight if:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Form breaks down (e.g., back rounds on rows, shoulders flare on bench)</li>
<li>You’re grinding to failure (0 RIR) on early sets</li>
<li>Sleep, nutrition, or joint recovery is compromised</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3>🔁 If Weight Stalls: Use These Progression Levers</h3>
<p>Hypertrophy isn’t just about heavier weights. Rotate these when progress plateaus:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Rep density</strong>: Same weight, same reps, but cut rest by 10–15s</li>
<li><strong>Eccentric control</strong>: 3-second lowering phase, pause at stretch</li>
<li><strong>Set volume</strong>: Add 1 hard set per exercise (cap at 16–20/muscle/week)</li>
<li><strong>Exercise variation</strong>: Swap to a biomechanically similar movement (e.g., barbell row → chest-supported row) to reset the stimulus</li>
<li><strong>RIR manipulation</strong>: Start a mesocycle at 3 RIR, finish at 1 RIR over 4–6 weeks</li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h3>📉 When &amp; How to Deload</h3>
<p>Progressive overload requires recovery cycles. Deload every <strong>4–8 weeks</strong> or when:</p>
<ul>
<li>Strength drops 2+ weeks straight</li>
<li>Joints ache, sleep suffers, or motivation tanks</li>
<li>RIR feels artificially high despite normal weights</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Deload protocol:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Keep weight the same</li>
<li>Cut sets by 40–50%</li>
<li>Maintain technique quality</li>
<li>Return to normal volume next week (you’ll often come back stronger)</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3>📊 Simple Tracking Template</h3>
<p>Log this after every session:</p>
<pre><code>Exercise | Weight | Reps (Set 1/2/3) | RIR | Notes
Bench    | 135    | 10/9/9          | 2   | Felt solid, add 5 lbs next week
Lat PD   | 110    | 11/10/10        | 1   | Last set form broke, repeat weight
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Review weekly:</strong> If you progressed → next step. If not → adjust recovery, swap a lever, or deload.</p>
<hr>
<h3>🚫 3 Common Mistakes That Kill Gains</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Adding weight every session</strong> → leads to form breakdown &amp; injury</li>
<li><strong>Training to failure on every set</strong> → spikes fatigue, reduces weekly volume quality</li>
<li><strong>Switching exercises weekly</strong> → impossible to track true progress</li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h3>🔜 Next Step</h3>
<p>Want a <strong>printable progression tracker</strong> pre-filled with your Upper/Lower exercises, rep ranges, and RIR targets? Or should we map out your first 4-week progression cycle with exact week-by-week weight/reps targets?</p></div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </article>

