                <div class="bubble"><h1>Heated Toilet Seats &amp; Electricity</h1>
<p><strong>Short answer: Yes, all heated toilet seats need to be plugged in.</strong></p>
<p>Heat requires electricity. There&#x27;s no battery-powered or water-heated alternative that&#x27;s practical.</p>
<h2>Why?</h2>
<ul>
<li>Heating elements need electrical power</li>
<li>Batteries would drain quickly (impractical)</li>
<li>Water heaters aren&#x27;t built into toilet seats</li>
</ul>
<h2>Exception?</h2>
<p>Some very high-end Japanese models have <strong>solar panels</strong> as a gimmick, but they still need to be plugged in as backup — not practical for bathrooms.</p>
<h2>So Your Options Are</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Non-heated bidet</strong> (like Tushy 3.0) — no plug needed</li>
<li><strong>Heated bidet/seat</strong> — requires outlet nearby</li>
</ol>
<p>There&#x27;s no middle ground where you get heat without electricity.</p>
<h2>If You Want Heat But No Outlet</h2>
<ul>
<li>Install a new outlet (electrician job, ~$100-300)</li>
<li>Use a long extension cord (not ideal)</li>
<li>Accept cold water</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p><strong>Bottom line:</strong> If heating is important to you and there&#x27;s no outlet near your toilet, that&#x27;s something to solve before buying a heated model. Otherwise, the Tushy 3.0 works great as-is without any power source.</p></div>
